{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-post-tsx","path":"/2018/10/18/blender-tutorial-6-outliner-layers-groups-hierarchies-scenes/","result":{"data":{"markdownRemark":{"html":"<p><em>In this new post of the series Blender tutorial I will talk about outliner, layers, groups, hierarchies and scenes.</em></p>\n<hr>\n<p>In the <a href=\"/2018/08/21/blender-tutorial-5-advanced-modeling/\">previous post of the series \"Blender tutorial\"</a> we talked\nabout advanced modeling in Blender. In this post we will continue to explore the capabilities of Blender by analyzing\noutliner, layers, groups, hierarchies and scenes.<br>\nLet's start from the <strong>outliner</strong>. This one contains the complete list of the objects contained in the scene. Each on of\nthem is represented with its material and geometry. It is possible to rename a mesh by <em>right clicking</em> on it and\nchoosing <em>rename</em>. To the right of each mesh we have the <em>restriction column</em>. It contains 3 buttons:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><em>the first button let us hide meshes in the 3D window</em></li>\n<li><em>the second button let us set a mesh as not selectable</em></li>\n<li><em>the third button let us hide meshes from the final renderer</em></li>\n</ul>\n<p><figure class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figure\" style=\"\">\n    <span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 1140px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/9357a59c906552f70f288355f9cb12ea/c58a3/blender-outliner.jpg\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 63.15789473684211%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/jpeg;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"The outliner\"\n        title=\"The outliner\"\n        src=\"/static/9357a59c906552f70f288355f9cb12ea/0470c/blender-outliner.jpg\"\n        srcset=\"/static/9357a59c906552f70f288355f9cb12ea/6c669/blender-outliner.jpg 285w,\n/static/9357a59c906552f70f288355f9cb12ea/882a4/blender-outliner.jpg 570w,\n/static/9357a59c906552f70f288355f9cb12ea/0470c/blender-outliner.jpg 1140w,\n/static/9357a59c906552f70f288355f9cb12ea/c58a3/blender-outliner.jpg 1500w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 1140px) 100vw, 1140px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span>\n    <figcaption class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figcaption\">The outliner</figcaption>\n  </figure></p>\n<p>Now let's talk about <strong>layers</strong>. We can find the layer panel at the bottom of the 3D window. Each layer is represented\nwith a button similar to a checkbox. We can turn on/off a layer by clicking on their corresponding button. We can add a\nmesh to a specific layer by selecting the layer and creating the mesh we want (primitive or import it). We can also move\nlayer by using the <em>m key</em> shortcut or by using the menu <em>Object -> Move to layer</em>.</p>\n<p><figure class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figure\" style=\"\">\n    <span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 1140px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/d9ef4fd3bd67148a5b49ded20f8cbf0c/c58a3/blender-layers.jpg\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 63.15789473684211%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/jpeg;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"The layers panel\"\n        title=\"The layers panel\"\n        src=\"/static/d9ef4fd3bd67148a5b49ded20f8cbf0c/0470c/blender-layers.jpg\"\n        srcset=\"/static/d9ef4fd3bd67148a5b49ded20f8cbf0c/6c669/blender-layers.jpg 285w,\n/static/d9ef4fd3bd67148a5b49ded20f8cbf0c/882a4/blender-layers.jpg 570w,\n/static/d9ef4fd3bd67148a5b49ded20f8cbf0c/0470c/blender-layers.jpg 1140w,\n/static/d9ef4fd3bd67148a5b49ded20f8cbf0c/c58a3/blender-layers.jpg 1500w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 1140px) 100vw, 1140px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span>\n    <figcaption class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figcaption\">The layers panel</figcaption>\n  </figure></p>\n<p>Another way to organize our objects is by using <strong>groups</strong>. With groups you can select multiple objects at once. We can\ncreate groups and add an object to an existing group by using the menu in the property panel or by using the <em>ctrl + g\nkeys</em> shortcut.</p>\n<p><figure class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figure\" style=\"\">\n    <span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 1140px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/971d7ae549853f8353d438f5f7ec4987/c58a3/blender-groups.jpg\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 63.15789473684211%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/jpeg;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"Groups, a way to select multiple object at once\"\n        title=\"Groups, a way to select multiple object at once\"\n        src=\"/static/971d7ae549853f8353d438f5f7ec4987/0470c/blender-groups.jpg\"\n        srcset=\"/static/971d7ae549853f8353d438f5f7ec4987/6c669/blender-groups.jpg 285w,\n/static/971d7ae549853f8353d438f5f7ec4987/882a4/blender-groups.jpg 570w,\n/static/971d7ae549853f8353d438f5f7ec4987/0470c/blender-groups.jpg 1140w,\n/static/971d7ae549853f8353d438f5f7ec4987/c58a3/blender-groups.jpg 1500w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 1140px) 100vw, 1140px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span>\n    <figcaption class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figcaption\">Groups, a way to select multiple object at once</figcaption>\n  </figure></p>\n<p>After layers and group we have <strong>scenes</strong>. Scenes allow us to create different set of our objects or new set with new\nobject inside our project. We can create and manage scenes by using the outliner and the ad hoc menu at the top of the\n3D window. We can create scenes that:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>are linked together: this means that a modification to one mesh in a scenes will be reflected also in the other.</li>\n<li>separated scene: this means that a modification to one mesh in a scenes will NOT be reflected also in the other.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><figure class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figure\" style=\"\">\n    <span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 1140px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/8e40dd724eb36eb6d0021cdcfe5d76fa/c58a3/blender-scene.jpg\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 63.15789473684211%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/jpeg;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"An example of a Blender scene\"\n        title=\"An example of a Blender scene\"\n        src=\"/static/8e40dd724eb36eb6d0021cdcfe5d76fa/0470c/blender-scene.jpg\"\n        srcset=\"/static/8e40dd724eb36eb6d0021cdcfe5d76fa/6c669/blender-scene.jpg 285w,\n/static/8e40dd724eb36eb6d0021cdcfe5d76fa/882a4/blender-scene.jpg 570w,\n/static/8e40dd724eb36eb6d0021cdcfe5d76fa/0470c/blender-scene.jpg 1140w,\n/static/8e40dd724eb36eb6d0021cdcfe5d76fa/c58a3/blender-scene.jpg 1500w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 1140px) 100vw, 1140px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span>\n    <figcaption class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figcaption\">An example of a Blender scene</figcaption>\n  </figure></p>\n<p>Last but not least we have <strong>hierarchies</strong>. We can create hierarchies of objects by selecting them and by choosing *\nObject ->  Parent*. Here we can find all the possible type of parental relationships that we can create. After creating\na hierarchies of objects, they will be shown grouped in the outliner. We will use hierarchies extensively when we will\ntalk about animation.</p>\n<p><figure class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figure\" style=\"\">\n    <span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 1140px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/e29b12d42d6c35a2dd81aa819038d194/c58a3/blender-hierarchies.jpg\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 63.50877192982456%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/jpeg;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"Hierarchies of objects\"\n        title=\"Hierarchies of objects\"\n        src=\"/static/e29b12d42d6c35a2dd81aa819038d194/0470c/blender-hierarchies.jpg\"\n        srcset=\"/static/e29b12d42d6c35a2dd81aa819038d194/6c669/blender-hierarchies.jpg 285w,\n/static/e29b12d42d6c35a2dd81aa819038d194/882a4/blender-hierarchies.jpg 570w,\n/static/e29b12d42d6c35a2dd81aa819038d194/0470c/blender-hierarchies.jpg 1140w,\n/static/e29b12d42d6c35a2dd81aa819038d194/c58a3/blender-hierarchies.jpg 1500w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 1140px) 100vw, 1140px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span>\n    <figcaption class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figcaption\">Hierarchies of objects</figcaption>\n  </figure></p>\n<p>In the next post we will talk about materials.</p>","frontmatter":{"title":"Blender tutorial: outliner, layers, groups, hierarchies and scenes","comments":true,"authors":["fabrizio_duroni"],"tags":["test driven development","agile","clean code"],"date":"18 Oct 2018","description":"In this new post of the series Blender tutorial I will talk about outliner, layers, groups, hierarchies and scenes.","math":false,"image":{"childImageSharp":{"gatsbyImageData":{"layout":"fullWidth","backgroundColor":"#181818","images":{"fallback":{"src":"/static/9357a59c906552f70f288355f9cb12ea/d97ee/blender-outliner.jpg","srcSet":"/static/9357a59c906552f70f288355f9cb12ea/e592c/blender-outliner.jpg 750w,\n/static/9357a59c906552f70f288355f9cb12ea/1d14e/blender-outliner.jpg 1080w,\n/static/9357a59c906552f70f288355f9cb12ea/c811e/blender-outliner.jpg 1366w,\n/static/9357a59c906552f70f288355f9cb12ea/d97ee/blender-outliner.jpg 1500w","sizes":"100vw"},"sources":[{"srcSet":"/static/9357a59c906552f70f288355f9cb12ea/f06bf/blender-outliner.webp 750w,\n/static/9357a59c906552f70f288355f9cb12ea/8c7d4/blender-outliner.webp 1080w,\n/static/9357a59c906552f70f288355f9cb12ea/fa1e8/blender-outliner.webp 1366w,\n/static/9357a59c9065